This example shows how to automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document.  We'll use sectioning commands to structure the document and the `\tableofcontents` command to generate the ToC.  The `hyperref` package is included for clickable links in the PDF output.


```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{hyperref} % For clickable links in the ToC

\begin{document}

\title{My Document with Automatic Table of Contents}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section of my document.  It provides a brief overview of the topics covered.

\section{Methods}
This section describes the methods used in the research.  It includes details about the experimental setup and data analysis techniques.

\subsection{Data Collection}
This subsection details the data collection process.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
This subsection describes the data analysis techniques employed.

\section{Results}
This section presents the results of the research.  The findings are summarized and discussed.

\section{Discussion}
This section discusses the implications of the research findings.  It also suggests future research directions.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document by summarizing the key findings and contributions.

\end{document}
```

To compile this code, you'll need a LaTeX compiler (like pdflatex). Save the code as a `.tex` file (e.g., `mydocument.tex`), and then compile it twice. The first compilation creates the auxiliary files needed to generate the table of contents, and the second compilation incorporates the ToC into the final PDF.  The `hyperref` package ensures that the page numbers in the ToC are clickable links.

