The most common way to automatically generate a table of contents in LaTeX is using the `\tableofcontents` command.  This command relies on the `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc., commands to identify the sections to be included.  LaTeX automatically creates the table of contents based on these sectioning commands.

Here's a complete example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\title{My Document}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\maketitle
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction to my document.

\subsection{First Subsection}
This is the first subsection.

\subsubsection{First Subsubsection}
This is the first subsubsection.

\section{Main Body}
This is the main body of my document.

\subsection{Second Subsection}
This is the second subsection.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion of my document.


\end{document}
```

To compile this code, you'll need a LaTeX compiler (like pdflatex).  The compilation process (typically involving running `pdflatex` multiple times) will generate the table of contents automatically. The `\tableofcontents` command tells LaTeX to insert the table of contents at that point in the document.


**Explanation:**

* `\documentclass{article}`: Specifies the document class.
* `\maketitle`:  Prints the title, author, and date.
* `\tableofcontents`: This is the crucial command that generates the table of contents.  It must be placed *after* the `\maketitle` command and *before* the sections it should include.
* `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`: These commands define the structure of the document and are used by LaTeX to populate the table of contents.


This simple example demonstrates the automatic generation of a table of contents.  More complex documents with custom styles or additional features might require more advanced techniques, but this fundamental method is sufficient for most cases.  Remember to compile your LaTeX file multiple times to ensure the table of contents is correctly generated.

