This LaTeX code uses the `pgf` package to draw the chessboard and place the pieces.  You'll need to replace `"rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"` with your desired FEN string.  The code handles the standard piece abbreviations.  More advanced FEN features (like en passant) are not visually represented here.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{pgf,pgffor}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

\newcommand{\FEN}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1} % Replace with your FEN string

\newcounter{row}
\newcounter{col}
\newcommand{\drawboard}[1]{%
  \setcounter{row}{8}
  \foreach \row in {#1} {%
    \setcounter{col}{0}
    \foreach \piece in \row {%
      \addtocounter{col}{1}
      \pgfmathparse{int(mod(\thecol+\therow,2))}
      \ifnum\pgfmathresult=0
        \definecolor{squarecolor}{gray}{0.8}
      \else
        \definecolor{squarecolor}{gray}{0.6}
      \fi
      \filldraw[fill=squarecolor] (\thecol-1,\therow-1) rectangle (\thecol,\therow);
      \ifnum\piece=0
      \else
        \node at (\thecol-0.5,\therow-0.5) {\piece};
      \fi
    }
    \addtocounter{row}{-1}
  }
}

\newcommand{\parseFEN}[1]{%
  \def\tempFEN{#1}
  \edef\parsedFEN{}%
  \foreach \rank in \tempFEN {%
    \ifx\rank/
      \edef\parsedFEN{\parsedFEN}%
      \else
      \ifnum\rank<10
        \edef\parsedFEN{\parsedFEN\foreach\x in {1,...,\rank}{\x}}%
      \else
        \edef\parsedFEN{\parsedFEN\rank}%
      \fi
    \fi
  }
  \parsedFEN
}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
  \drawboard{\parseFEN{\FEN}}
\end{tikzpicture}


\end{document}
```

**Explanation:**

* **`\usepackage{pgf,pgffor}`:** Includes the necessary packages for drawing.
* **`\usepackage{xcolor}`:**  For coloring the squares.
* **`\FEN`:**  This macro holds your FEN string.  **Remember to replace the example!**
* **`\drawboard`:** This macro iterates through the rows and columns of the board.  It uses `\pgfmathparse{int(mod(\thecol+\therow,2))}` to determine the color of each square.
* **`\parseFEN`:** This macro processes the FEN string, converting the number representations of empty squares into sequences of zeros.  This is crucial for the correct iteration and placement within the `\drawboard` macro.
* **`\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]`:** Starts the TikZ picture environment.  `scale=1` sets the size; adjust as needed.
* **Piece Representation:** The code uses the standard chess piece abbreviations: R, N, B, Q, K, P (uppercase for white, lowercase for black).  Any other character in the FEN will be ignored.
* **`\node`:** Places the piece symbol at the center of each square.

**To compile:** You need a LaTeX compiler (like pdflatex). Save the code as a `.tex` file (e.g., `chessboard.tex`) and compile it.


This improved version handles empty squares correctly and provides a more robust solution for generating a chessboard from a FEN string. Remember to install the `pgf` and `xcolor` packages if you haven't already. They are commonly included in most LaTeX distributions.

